  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The forthcoming book, \"Plutarch and Rhetoric,\" published by Leuven University Press in 2024, is poised to contribute significantly to the discourse surrounding the intersection of classical literature and rhetorical studies.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Plutarch and Rhetoric,\" set to be published in 2024, emphasizes the relevance of classical texts in shaping contemporary rhetorical frameworks. This scholarly work engages with the nuances of Plutarch's writings to uncover insights that resonate with modern rhetorical practices, thereby broadening the scope of rhetorical scholarship.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's strong commercial linkage is evident through its presence on prominent retail platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads, indicating a potential for wider readership beyond academia. This commercial visibility suggests an interest in the topic that extends into popular discourse, allowing the themes explored in the text to reach a more general audience.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">While the current data indicates no initial citations or community discourse, the academic rigor and methodological framework within the book position it well for future scholarly engagement. Scholars in the fields of classical studies and rhetoric may find the book's interpretations timely and relevant, leading to its incorporation into curriculum and subsequent academic dialogues.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Lastly, as a project with an inferred emphasis on sustainability and policy relevance through a significant association with one Sustainable Development Goal, \"Plutarch and Rhetoric\" not only contributes to scholarly literature but also aligns with broader societal objectives. This dual relevance enhances its potential impact on both academic scholarship and policy discussions related to education and communication.</p>",
